{"questionId":"2948837","questionHtml":"<p>Use mathematical induction to prove your conjecture from part (e). You may assume that, for any value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><munder><mi>lim</mi><mrow><mi>b</mi><mo>→</mo><mo>∞</mo></mrow></munder><msup><mi>x</mi><mi>m</mi></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>Note:</strong> Accept starting at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>, throughout this proof.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>!</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>M1A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>M1</strong></em> for considering the case where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>, and <em><strong>A1</strong></em> if it is clear that both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>!</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math> have been considered.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>so true for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p>\n<p>assume true for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi></math>, (<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>k</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mo>∫</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>∞</mo></msubsup><msup><mi>x</mi><mi>k</mi></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>!</mo></math>)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>M0</strong></em> for statements such as “let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi></math>”.</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Subsequent marks after this <em><strong>M1</strong></em> are independent of this mark and can be awarded.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>when <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p>\n<p>attempt to integrate by parts&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> To obtain the <em><strong>M1</strong></em>, a minimum of an expression +/- an integral must be seen.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mo>∫</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>∞</mo></msubsup><msup><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><mn>0</mn><mo>∞</mo></msubsup><mo>+</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo><msubsup><mo>∫</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>∞</mo></msubsup><msup><mi>x</mi><mi>k</mi></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>x</mi></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo><msubsup><mo>∫</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>∞</mo></msubsup><msup><mi>x</mi><mi>k</mi></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>x</mi></math> simplified to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>!</mo></math> seen&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>(</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>!</mo></math></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Condone omission of the zero.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>!</mo></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>Hence if true for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi></math> then also true for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></math>. As true for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math> so true for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>∈</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℤ</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award the final <em><strong>R1</strong></em> mark provided at least four of the previous marks are gained.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[8 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"2948837","referenceCode":"23M.3.AHL.TZ1.1f","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Use mathematical induction to prove your conjecture from part (e). You may assume that, for any value of m, limb→∞xme-x=0.","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"f","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 8]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","AHL 5.16—Integration by substitution, parts and repeated parts","Topic 1—Number and algebra","AHL 1.15—Proof by induction, contradiction, counterexamples"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}